SUMMARIZER="F">  

The Exxon Valdez, a California-bound oil tanker, struck a reef and
spilled 8.4M gallons of crude in Alaska's Prince William Sound on 24
March.  A US Fish and Wildlife Service representative said the
987-foot tanker was spilling oil at the rate of 10,000 barrels an
hour. But a Coast Guard spokesman said that the spill had slowed to a
trickle by afternoon Friday and did not seem to be moving ashore.
Environmentalists feared that wildlife would be threatened, especially
if the oil reached shore, and were concerned about the slow pace of
the cleanup.  Alaskan Governor Cowper arrived in Valdez on Friday to
evaluate the spill.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890325-0029"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="F">
 
Calm waters of Prince William Sound stymied efforts to disperse the
largest oil spill in US history.  The spill of 11.3M gallons occurred
when the Exxon Valdez struck Bligh Reef 25 miles from Valdez, Alaska.
Exxon officials planned to pump oil remaining on the Valdez onto
another Exxon tanker.  A spill of this size in a complex environment
promises to be a cleanup nightmare.  The Valdez had been loaded at the
Alyeska Pipeline Service Co.  with crude from the Trans-Alaska
pipeline.  Alyeska must now operate at reduced rate and its capacity
would allow nine days of operation before it would shut down.  Valdez
relies on fishing, oil, and tourism.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890325-0143"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="F"> 
 
The biggest oil spill in US history created a slick seven miles long
and seven wide in Prince William Sound from 240,000 barrels of crude
from the Exxon Valdez.  The Golob Oil Pollution Bulletin called this a
major environmental catastrophe and that clean-up equipment at the
site was grossly inadequate.  Alaska has a plan for action within five
hours of a spill but it took hours longer and insufficient equipment
was employed initially.  A Greenpeace spokesman said the whole food
chain could be affected.  A Coast Guard spokesman said some
blood-alcohol tests were given to crew but no results yet available.
National Transportation Safety Board officials were expected on site
soon.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890326-0081"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="F">
        
The Exxon Valdez was illegally piloted by its third mate, who didn't
have a proper pilot's license, when the vessel ran aground.  Exxon
said the captain, Joseph Hazelwood, was not on the bridge at the time
of the the accident, contrary to company policy.  The captain and two
crew members were relieved of duty and subpoenaed by the NSTB.  Two
supertankers remained anchored offshore by the closure of the Valdez
port.  Alaska's governor declared the pristine Prince William Sound a
disaster area.  The Coast Guard estimated the spill as covering 100
square miles.  Many fishermen expected minimal harvests and long term
damage to its reputation.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA032789-0038"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="F">
    
An unqualified mate was piloting the Exxon Valdez when it crashed into
rocks resulting in the worst oil spill in US history.  The Long
Beach-bound tanker was actually involved in two separate accidents,
first hitting a jagged rock pinnacle a mile outside shipping lanes,
then after going two more miles, hit more underwater rocks.  Exxon did
not know if Captain Hazelwood took the wheel before the second
accident.  Mate Gregory Cousins did not have Coast Guard certification
to pilot through the Sound. The International Bird Rescue Center set
up a rehabilitation center and experts from the Hubbs Marine Research
Institute in San Diego were to arrive today.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890404-0260"
