SUMMARIZER="F"> 
 
Exxon crews finished pumping the remaining crude from the Exxon
Valdez, preparing to refloat the vessel.  Exxon planned to pump air
into the hold to aid in refloating the vessel.  They said that the
oil-catching boom put around the ship after an 11 hour delay, could
have touched off an explosion of gases from the oil. The family of
fired Exxon Valdez captain, Joseph Hazelwood, said he wanted to
surrender but awaits advice from counsel.  The state told fishermen it
would not allow a herring season this year.  Ordinally, a harvest is
usually worth about $12M.  Sablefish and shrimp fisheries have also
been closed.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA040689-0056"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="F">  
 
Exxon salvage crews successfully refloated the stricken tanker Exxon
Valdez after nearly 1M barrels of oil were pumped to smaller tankers
and air was forced into the Valdez tanks.  Clean-up from the spill
continued as the oil slick was estimated to affect an area the size of
Delaware.  Alaska Governor Cowper said the coast Guard could better
handle the clean-up than Exxon.  James Hazelwood, captain of the
Valdez, who had been found to be legally drunk and was fired by Exxon,
surrendered to police in a Long Island suburb of New York City.
Released on $500,000 bail he may not waive extradition to
Alaska.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA040789-0051"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="F">   
 
Alaska Gov Cowper threatened to close down the trans-Alaska pipeline
unless owners met measures for improved safety and clean-up, namely:
description of dedicated clean-up gear, names of 12 response teams
available 24 hours a day, installation of containment booms around
tankers in harbor, restrict tanker traffic to daylight, limit to
loading one tanker at a time until all equipment in place, and show
that adequate gear and supplies are available to handle another 10M
gallon spill.  Former Exxon Valdez captain Joseph Hazelwood left jail
in New York after a judge cut his bail from $500,000 to $25,000.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA043089-0197"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="F">
   
A fresh oil sheen has seeped from the ruptured Exxon Valdez making a
complete clean-up impossible.  The vessel is now undergoing temporary
repairs 30 miles from the rupture site. The Alaskan Senate passed
bills to add to state's spill response fund, prevent companies from
deducting spill costs from oil production taxes, develop state
contingency plans, establish a spill response team, and create a
commission to investigate the Exxon Valdez spill.  It is unlikely that
the House would approve the bill before adjournment.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890501-0176"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="F">
 
Exxon has a revised plan for cleaning 364 miles of Alaskan coastline
fouled by the nation's largest oil spill, but the plan is to end in
September and would require suspension of local environmental laws.
Sludge and tar from the spill fouled beaches of Katmai National Park
killing animals and birds and even threatening the huge brown bears.
The damage extended southwest of Valdez for some 500 miles.  Coast
Guard Admiral Yost would decide whether to approve the plan within a
week.  The oil industry blames the spill for increase in crude prices
and higher costs at the gas pumps.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890502-0205"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="F"> 
 
Coast Guard Commandant Yost attacked Exxon's plan to clean up the
Alaskan oil spill.  Also, consumer activist Ralph Nader, other
environmentalists, and politicians expressed anger in a one day
"Boycott Exxon" campaign.  The cleanup is to be paid for by the oil
industry and could add $100-500M to Alaska's economy, more than
offsetting the loss to the fishing industry.  Thousands of dead birds
were spotted 300 miles from the spill site.  Since the Exxon Valdez
spill, gas prices have increased 10% nationally and as much as 25% in
the Northwest.  Nebraska's two senators have asked the US Attorney
General to investigate possible price gouging by the oil
industry.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA012590-0174"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="F">
   
Exxon increased its estimate of the 1989 costs of cleaning up the most
expensive environmental disaster in history to $2B and it could take
another $500M.  Exxon noted that these costs were the major reason for
their lower net income for the year, but analysts said that Exxon's
size would insulate it from serious long-term financial damage.
Exxon's stock has lagged behind that of major oil firms and Exxon
could suffer from continuing negative publicity from the Valdez spill
and the subsequent heating oil spill into a waterway between New York
and New Jersey.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900313-0191"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="F">
    
From a helicopter, the Alaskan beach appears untouched by the worst
oil spill in US history but hundreds of gallons of oil are locked up
under the surface.  A year after the wreck of the Exxon Valdez, dead
birds no longer wash up onto the beach but thousands were killed
earlier.  Exxon notes that the spill did not wipe out any species and
that surviving animals can rebuild populations.  But the US Fish and
Wildlife Service says that could take 70 years. Joseph Hazelwood is on
trial for drunken driving of the vessel as captain.  Criminal
indictments have been issued against Exxon and they also face more
than 150 civil lawsuits.</SUM>


<SUM
